Patch Set 46: Code-Review+2
Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as 17c472452c9a3518aeac636d01b8e2f01c4fa21f
If anyone is curious, it's this line.
Acknowledged
I probably should've specified, this is a theoretical error that a static analyzer flagged.  I'm still looking at it, but wanted to keep it in my stack as I work through this stuff.
it's funny, any attempt to simplify this causes clang to suddenly start flagging the same error.  I wonder if we just made code that was complex enough that tidy gave up.
Done

The static analysis tools flag std::format as throwing?
Why are they unhappy with this std::format and not others? E.g. line 82, or any other places we use it https://github.com/search?q=repo%3Aopenbmc%2Fbmcweb%20std%3A%3Aformat&type=code

Those are all excellent questions;  I spent a lot of time trying to find answers to that, and couldn't.  You can see me pushing many different variations of patch on this review to try to play with what flags and what doesn't.  I'd normally think of it as a false positive, but multiple static analysis tools including clang-tidy are now flagging it when we simplify the code in a change that didn't change anything.  (one static analysis tool was flagging before we simplified).

My guesses here are:
1. We're moving an object that the moved object has the potential to throw.
2. The libstdc++ implementation doesn't correctly mark this variant as noexcept.
3. We're accidentally throwing in a std::formatted.

There are several advantages to this patch, and I want to see it get in. 
This stinks we have to have this but to keep the static analysis tools I am okay with it. You have a comment explaining the try/catch.
The thing I'd also say is that I'm still looking into this, so with any luck, I might be able to fix it in the future.
Ack.
